&#xa0;
[normal]Written Evidence – Department for Transport[bold] (HCS0005)[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]1.1.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]The Department for Transport’s written evidence is limited to the factual information that it has at its disposal and that it is able to
[normal] provide without prejudicing the ongoing Investigations by the Air Accidents Investigation Branch into recent accidents involving the Eurocopter Super Puma helicopter, the Civil Aviation Authority (CAA) Review into North Sea Helicopter Operations, and the 
[normal]Fatal Accident Inquiry in respect of Eurocopter Super Puma helicopter crash in April 2009, due to commence in January 2014.  Details of the accidents and previous air accident reports are available at 
[normal]http://www.aaib.gov.uk/publications/index.cfm
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1.2.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]The Department for Transport acknowledges that there are approximately 57,000 individuals working in the 
[normal]North Sea
[normal], across 600 facilities. The only viable means of transferring workers in the 
[normal]North Sea
[normal] industry from shore to installation and from one installation to another is by helicopter. Three 
[normal]UK
[normal] helicopter companies operate approximately 100 aircraft in support of the exploitation of oil and gas around the 
[normal]UK
[normal]: Bristow Helicopters Ltd; Bond Offshore
[normal] Helicopters Ltd; and CHC Scotia Ltd.  Main operating bases are: 
[normal]Aberdeen
[normal]; Scatsta; 
[normal]Norwich
[normal]; North Denes; Humberside; and 
[normal]Blackpool
[normal].  There are approximately 100 flights per day. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1.3.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]Offshore helicopter operations represent a small section of 
[normal]UK
[normal] aviation. Ho
[normal]wever, it provides critical support to the oil and gas industry, which is of significant economic importance. It is recognised by both industry and the CAA that these non-scheduled public transport operations take place in a hostile environment and are rel
[normal]atively high risk. Therefore helicopter operations in the 
[normal]North Sea
[normal] are worthy of particular attention.  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1.4.
[normal]&#xa0; 
