[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]3.1.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]The CAA oversight regime covers flight operations and flying training, aircraft maintenance, aerodromes
[normal] and air traffic control.  Specialists also cover dangerous goods and cabin safety aspects.  Condition and suitability of helicopter landing deck areas on offshore installations are overseen by the independent Helideck Certification Agency, which is audite
[normal]d by CAA specialists.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.2.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]Audits and inspections take place on a rolling schedule at each company headquarters and at all operating bases against specific requirements informed by best practice judgement.  The subsequent schedule is determined against previou
[normal]s company performance, and the CAA will vary oversight accordingly.  Many aspects, including management arrangements, company procedures, training and records are assessed and flight checks take place on public transport flights.  
[normal]The CAA maintain a c
[normal]lose 
[normal]liaison is with each operator between formal visits, and regular meetings occur.  
[normal]CAA inspectors
[normal] are qual
[normal]ified and experienced personnel
[normal], trained in 
[normal]auditing techniques and, in the case of flight operations assessments, qualified pilots fly on selected fli
[normal]ghts to ensure safe practices and that company procedures are being followed.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.3.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]I
[normal]nspectors may make “Findings of N
[normal]on-
[normal]C
[normal]ompliance
[normal]”
[normal] and the operator is required to resolve these issues within an agreed timescale.  
[normal]“
[normal]Significant Findings
[normal]”
[normal] 
[normal]are
[normal] require 
[normal]by the CAA 
[normal]to be resolved immediately.  Regulatory tools for poor safety performance include an 
[normal]“
[normal]On Notice Procedure
[normal]”
[normal], temporary suspension or, ultimately, revocation of an approval.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.4.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]There are two resident foreign helicopter operators based at 
[normal]Norwich
[normal] and Wick: NHV from 
[normal]Belgium
[normal]; and Dancopter from 
[normal]Denmark
[normal].  Oversight is the responsibility of their respective National Authority and the 
[normal]UK
[normal] can perform ‘ramp inspections’ under the International Civil Aviation Organisation protocols.  The CAA hosts a regul
[normal]ar joint offshore National Authorities’ group involving 
[normal]Norway
[normal], 
[normal]Denmark
[normal], 
[normal]Belgium
[normal], 
[normal]Holland
[normal], 
[normal]Germany
[normal] and 
[normal]Ireland
[normal], where information on operating practices is exchanged, and an informal agreement exists to attend their audits/inspections in 
[normal]UK
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.5.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]The CAA maint
[normal]ains close links with the oil and gas industry, as members of the safety steering and aviation technical groups, and manages a collaborative safety research committee to focus efforts to best benefit. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.6.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]Aviation regulation within the 
[normal]UK
[normal] is currently evolvi
[normal]ng from a national model to a pan-European model under the auspices of the European Aviation Safety Agency
[normal] (EASA)
[normal].  Whilst pilot licensing and aircraft manufacture, for example, are now subject directly to EU Regulations, the requirements for operating hel
[normal]icopters are founded on the UK Air Navigation Order 2009 and a collaborative rule-set developed within the European region.  This differs in other countries that operate offshore helicopters in 
[normal]Europe
[normal] because of their membership status of the EU, the varie
[normal]ty of national legal codes and differences in the adoption of international standards.  New Regulations for Air Operations will apply across the EU from 28 October 2014
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]4.1.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]Since the late 1980’
[normal]s, the CAA has been leading a programme of research aimed at improving the safety of offshore helicopter operations. The motivation for this initiative came from 
[normal]the
[normal] joint CAA/
[normal]i
[normal]ndustry review of helicopter airworthiness
[normal] by the Helicopter Airworthiness Revi
[normal]ew Panel (HARP)
[normal], commissioned in 1982
[normal]. This 
[normal]study led to a number of research projects and other reviews which, in turn, led to 
[normal]a well-founded data-driven programme of work for improving offshore helicopter safety
[normal]. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.2.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]The focus for HARP is to identify how 
[normal]new technology can be used to support and enable the introduction of enhanced standards. More recent accidents and the resulting AAIB Safety Recommendations have added impetus to these projects and have helped to support the voluntary implementation of the
[normal] research results by the industry. The research areas which relate directly to AAIB Safety Recommendations are as follows:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.3.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]The largest and arguably most 
[normal]significant area of research has been HUMS which potentially addresses the top three technical accident causes. HUMS comprises the collection and analysis of vibration data which is then analysed to detect defects before they compromise flight safety. HUMS
[normal] was voluntarily introduced by the industry with funding from the offshore oil company operators in the early 1990s following the CAA-run in-service trials. There was a significant reduction in the accident rate due to technical causes around this time and
[normal] it is considered reasonable to assume that HUMS was largely responsible. However, the CAA has said, there is room for improvement in HUMS and the latest research on advanced data analysis techniques is presently being introduced, again, voluntarily by the
[normal] industry again with funding from the offshore oil company operators. It is also the case that HUMS has only been applied to transmissions and its extension to rotors is being progressed, currently via participation in the AgustaWestland Rotorcraft Technol
[normal]ogy Validation Programme (RTVP) part funded by the Technology Strategy Board (TSB).
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.4.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]Some proactive research has also been undertaken, the most notable example of which is the application of Flight Data Monitoring (FDM) to offshore helicopter operations. T
[normal]his highly successful research project resulted in implementation of the scheme including all of the 
[normal]UK
[normal] offshore helicopter operators and its addition as a Recommended Practice for Flight Data Recorder (FDR) equipped helicopters in ICAO Annex 6 Part III. T
[normal]hrough 
[normal]the routine analysis of aircraft 
[normal]FDR
[normal] data
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]the 
[normal]monitor
[normal]ing of
[normal] 
[normal]pilot performance in terms of compliance with 
[normal]operational 
[normal]standards and good airmanship, FDM has the capability of reducing the number of accidents due to operational causes.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.5.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]In respect o
[normal]f external cause accidents, the CAA has recognised the need to address lightning strikes. Helicopters have the ability to ‘trigger’ lightning, and a helicopter triggered lightning forecasting system has been developed by the UK Met Office under a CAA-led r
[normal]esearch project. The system has shown significant promise when applied to data from past lightning strikes and is presently undergoing in-service trials with the 
[normal]UK
[normal] offshore helicopter operators.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.6.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]Also undergoing in-service trials is the first production v
[normal]ersion of the new helideck lighting system developed under a CAA-led research project. This new scheme directly addresses two of the more recent accidents, one of which involved 
[normal]fatalities, and the offshore oil industry has committed to voluntarily retrofi
[normal]t this equipment. In the photographs below, at top left is an actual photograph of a prototype of the new system, with a ‘simulation’ of the old scheme produced by photo editing at top right; the lower photograph is a close up of the production version of 
[normal]the equipment recently installed on the Centrica CPC-1 gas platform in Morecambe Bay.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.7.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]In addition to addressing the causes of accidents, research has also been undertaken in response to developments in the offshore industry. A current example 
[normal]is the work being performed on the anti-slip properties of aluminium helidecks. A potential future area of work falling within this category that is under consideration is the issue of turbulence generated by offshore wind turbines; this is a concern for t
[normal]he helicopters used to winch maintenance personnel onto them.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.8.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]Also on the subject of future work, in addition to the extension of HUMS to rotors previously mentioned, another significant area of research identified by HARP as yet unaddressed and that argu
[normal]ably deserves some attention is that of usage monitoring. This comprises the monitoring of the use of the helicopter, largely in terms of the combination of manner and duration of flight, in order to validate the design assumptions that lie behind the safe
[normal]-lives allocated to components, and which should form a key part of the continued airworthiness programme for an aircraft. Practical considerations have prevented any real progress in this area prior to the introduction of flight data monitoring, but consi
[normal]deration should now be given to reviewing the state of the art, especially in view of recent accidents which have highlighted scope for improvement in the general area of continued airworthiness.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.9.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]In summary, for a number of projects,  the research is esse
[normal]ntially complete and the focus has switched to promoting and supporting implementation by producing and publishing guidance material, influencing the industry and, where appropriate, by lobbying for changes to the requirements at EASA. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]5.1.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]The 
[normal]UK
[normal] helicopter safety research programme, Section 4.2 of the Civil Aviation Authority Safety Plan 2011 to 2013 (available at 
[normal]www.caa.co.uk
[normal]) has been jointly funded and 
[normal]monitored by the CAA-run Helicopter Safety Research Management Committee (HSRMC). The HSRMC was originally set up by CAA in the late 1980's to manage a joint CAA/UK Government/UK oil industry research fund that was created to progress the HARP recommendati
[normal]ons following the loss of 45 lives in the BV 234 Chinook accident in 1986. The committee is still thriving and has evolved over time expanding its membership to include the UK MoD, the UK helicopter operators (BHA), the European Aviation Safety Agency (EAS
[normal]A), the Norwegian CAA, the Norwegian oil industry (OLF), and the European Helicopter Association (EHA). A recently joined member (post the fatal Cougar Helicopters accident in 
[normal]Canada
[normal]) is the 
[normal]Canada
[normal] – Newfoundland/Labrador Offshore Petroleum Board (C-NLOPB)
[normal] who bring yet another perspective to the work of the committee.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]5.2.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]To date, the committee has overseen around £10M of research funding spread over a wide range of helicopter safety issues, covering reactive initiatives resulting from the HARP Report and 
[normal]subsequent AAIB Safety Recommendations, proactive research and work in support of the introduction of new technology. Currently, the extramural costs associated with new projects are provided by external contributors, normally HSRMC members. The intramural
[normal] costs of managing and administering research projects, and of running the HSRMC, are borne by the CAA. This arrangement helps to ensure that those who benefit from the research bear a fair share of the costs, and also ensures the ‘buy-in’ necessary for th
[normal]e research to be implemented as evidenced in the examples earlier in this paper. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]5.3.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]NB: CAA is participating in the EASA-led European Helicopter Safety Team (EHEST) initiative. Although offshore helicopter accidents have been included in the associated data
[normal] analysis exercise, the focus of EHEST is primarily on smaller helicopters and the onshore operations more prevalent across the European Union. EHEST is unlikely to adequately address the needs of 
[normal]UK
[normal] offshore helicopter operations.
